\end_inset

[One-qubit quantum probability space] Consider a one-qubit Hilbert space
 with states 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\ket{0}+\beta\ket{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha|^{2}+|\beta|^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The set of events associated with this Hilbert space consists of all projection
 operators.
 Each event is interpreted as a possible post-measurement state of a quantum
 system in current state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{0}$
\end_inset

 indicates that the post-measurement state will be
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{0}$
\end_inset

; the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{1}$
\end_inset

 indicates that the post-measurement state will be
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1}$
\end_inset

; the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{\ps}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ps}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(\ket{0}+\ket{1})$
\end_inset

 indicates that the post-measurement state will be 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ps}$
\end_inset

; the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{1}=\proj{0}+\proj{1}$
\end_inset

 indicates that the post-measurement state will be a linear combination
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1}$
\end_inset

; and the empty event 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{0}$
\end_inset

 states that the post-measurement state will be the empty state.
 As in the classical case, a probability measure is a function that maps
 events to 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

: here is a partial specification of a possible probability measure: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{rcl}
\mu\left(\mathbb{0}\right)=0,\quad\mu\left(\mathbb{1}\right)=1,\quad\mu\left(\proj{0}\right)=1,\quad\mu\left(\proj{1}\right)=0,\quad\mu\left(\proj{\ps}\right)=1/2,\quad\ldots\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

Note that, similarly to the classical case, the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{1}$
\end_inset

 is 1 and the probability of collections of orthogonal events (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{0}+\proj{1}$
\end_inset

) is the sum of the individual probabilities.
 In contrast, a collection of non-orthogonal events (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{\ps}$
\end_inset

) is not itself an event.
 In the classical example, we argued that each probability measure is uniquely
 determined by two actual coins.
 A similar (but much more subtle) argument is valid also in the quantum
 case.
 By postulates of quantum mechanics and Gleason's theorem, it turns out
 that for large enough quantum systems, each probability measure is uniquely
 determined by an actual quantum state.
 
